    <div class="doc-block">
    <h2>When to pick which</h2>

    <h3>Pick Nexrial if…</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>You need a full CTMS — visit scheduling, monitoring visit management, protocol deviation tracking, IRB submission tracking, SOP management, and invoice management in one system</li>
      <li>You want to evaluate pricing from a public page without a sales call</li>
      <li>You run 5–25 concurrent studies and your budget is under $700/month</li>
      <li>Your sponsor does not require a dedicated eISF product with a separate remote-access portal; Nexrial's regulatory binder covers basic document versioning and audit trail</li>
      <li>A formal validation package (VAL-PLAN, IQ/OQ/PQ, VAL-REPORT) for Part 11 documentation is important to your compliance team</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Pick Florence Healthcare if…</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Your primary need is a deeply capable eISF — document organization, version control, long-term archiving, and sponsor remote monitoring access at scale</li>
      <li>You are a sponsor or CRO that needs SiteLink for remote site document review across many sites, or an eTMF for central trial master file management</li>
      <li>Your sponsors already use Florence and require sites to connect via eBinders/SiteLink for remote monitoring visits</li>
      <li>You need eConsent workflow digitization as a primary requirement</li>
      <li>You are comfortable with contact-sales pricing and have a procurement process that accommodates undisclosed pricing</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Using both</h3>
    <p>
      Florence and Nexrial are not direct substitutes — they address different operational
      layers. A site that needs a robust eISF for sponsor connectivity (Florence eBinders)
      and a full CTMS for internal study operations (Nexrial) could run both. Whether the
      cost and complexity of two platforms is justified depends on your sponsor requirements
      and the volume of remote monitoring visits you host.
    </p>
